{{Infobox Cloud |name=Cirrus fibratus [[File:Cirrus front over Austnesfjorden, Austvågøya, Lofoten, Norway, 2015 April.jpg|thumb|center]] |image name=Cirrus fibratus |abbreviation=Ci fib |symbol=CH_1.png |genus=Cirrus (''curl of hair'') |species=fibratus (''fibrous'') |variety= |altitude_m=Above 6,000 |altitude_ft=Above 20,000 |appearance=fibers, threads<ref>{{cite web|title=Cirrus|url=http://www.clouds-online.com/cloud_atlas/cirrus/cirrus.htm|work=Cloud Atlas|accessdate=13 July 2011|author=Wolken Online}}</ref> |precipitation=No}} '''Cirrus fibratus''' is a type of [[cirrus cloud]]. The name ''cirrus fibratus'' is derived from [[Latin]], meaning "fibrous".<ref>{{cite web |title=Definition of fibratus, fibratus |url=http://latinlexicon.org/definition.php?p1=2022232&p2=f&p3=2 |accessdate=13 July 2011 |author=Numen - The Latin Lexicon}}</ref> These clouds are similar to [[cirrus uncinus]], commonly known as "mares' tails"; however, fibratus clouds do not have tufts or hooks at the end.<ref>{{cite book |last=Dunlop |first=Storm |title=The weather identification handbook |year=2003 |publisher=Lyons Press |location=Guilford, Conn. |isbn=1-58574-857-9 |pages=56 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BR2ft4G5TgQC&lpg=PA1&pg=PA56#v=onepage&q=fibratus&f=false |edition=1st Lyons Press |accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref> The filaments are usually separate from one another.<ref>{{cite web |last=Callanan |first=Martin |title=Cirrus fibratus |url=http://nephology.eu/cirrus/cirrus-fibratus |work=International Cloud Atlas |publisher=nephology.eu |accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref>
Like other [[cirrus cloud]]s, cirrus fibratus occur at high [[altitude]]s. They can indicate an approaching [[warm front]];<ref>{{cite web |title=Cumulus Clouds |url=http://www.wolstanton.org.uk/public_html/web_weather/web/gallery_clouds_cirrus.php|work=Clouds |accessdate=13 July 2011 |author=Wolstanton Weather|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327014352/http://www.wolstanton.org.uk/public_html/web_weather/web/gallery_clouds_cirrus.php|archivedate=27 March 2013}}</ref> however, they can also be an indication that fair weather will follow.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cirrus Fibratus (Ci fib) |url=http://www.theweatherobserver.com/?p=71 |accessdate=13 July 2011 |author=The Weather Observer}}</ref>
