{{Infobox protected area | name = Hammeren | alt_name = | iucn_category = III | photo = Hammershus - view of Hammeren.jpg | photo_alt = | photo_caption = Hammeren seen from [[Hammershus]] | photo_width = | map = Denmark Bornholm | map_alt = | map_caption = Location in Bornholm | map_width = | location = [[Bornholm]] island in [[Denmark]] | nearest_city = | coordinates = {{coords|55|17|40|N|14|46|39|E|display=inline, title}} | area = 600 | established = | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = | url = }}
'''Hammeren''' (also '''Hammerknuden'''; meaning, "hammerhead-shaped crag of granite")<ref name="denstoredanske.dk">{{cite web|url=http://www.denstoredanske.dk/Danmarks_geografi_og_historie/Danmarks_geografi/Bornholm/Hammeren|title=Hammeren|publisher=Den Store Danske|language=Danish|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref> is a protected area<ref name="protectedplanet.net">{{cite web|url=http://www.protectedplanet.net/sites/92389|title= Hammeren, Bornholm Protected by Conservation Order|work=protectedplanet.net|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref> and [[promontory]] in [[Denmark]] on the northernmost point of [[Bornholm]] island.<ref name="Norie1846">{{cite book|last=Norie|first=John William|title=Piloting directions for the Cattegat and Baltic, or East sea; also for the Sound and Belts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eCkEAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA39|accessdate=22 October 2012|edition=Public domain|year=1846|publisher=Wilson|pages=39–}}</ref> It projects into Sæne Bugt bay in the [[Baltic Sea]].<ref name="Stone2008">{{cite book|last=Stone|first=Andrew|title=Denmark|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m_gT1lQpZEAC&pg=PA196|accessdate=22 October 2012|date=1 February 2008|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=978-1-74104-669-4|page=196}}</ref> The area includes [[Hammersø]], the largest lake on the island and the only [[Tarn (lake)|tarn]] in Denmark,<ref name=Rapport>{{cite web|url=http://www.studienet.dk/Opgaver/Hammers%C3%B8en--24294.aspx|title=Rapport: Hammersøen|language=Danish|publisher=Studienet.dk|accessdate=2012-06-07}}</ref> and a hill, {{convert|276|ft}} in height, named Stejlebjerg (or Stieleberg). It is steep to the southwest but slopes gradually to the northeast, and is separated from the rest of the land by a valley.<ref name="USHydrographicOffice1917">{{cite book|author=United States. Hydrographic Office|title=Publications|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FoUPAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA108|accessdate=22 October 2012|edition=Public domain|year=1917|pages=108–}}</ref>
==Geography== Bornholm has varied natural features, such as [[Almindingen]], [[Jons Kapel]], [[Paradisbakkerne]], [[Rytterknægten]], and [[Dueodde]].<ref name="BlangstrupHalvorsen1894">{{cite book|last1=Blangstrup|first1=Johan Christian|last2=Halvorsen|first2=Jens Braage|last3=Fischer|first3=Karl Kristian Emil|title=Salmonsens store illustrerede konversationsleksikon: en nordisk encyklopædi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=240XAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA400|accessdate=23 October 2012|edition=Public domain|year=1894|publisher=Brødrene Salmonsen (J. Salmonsen)|language=Danish|pages=400–}}</ref> Hammeren has cliffs towering {{Convert|86|ft}} from the Baltic Sea and a rift valley separating it from the surroundings. It covers a rocky area of granite formations (considered one of the best examples of the kind)<ref name= "Porter2009">{{Cite book|last1= Porter fist1= Darwin|last2= Prince |first2= Danforth |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PC2CdFzlqf8C&pg=PA420&lpg=PA420&dq=Hammeren,+Denmark&source=bl&ots=F_h6GQFvJy&sig=_ld_PQn_FZamPkbGGczzxlxq8_U&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FwmGUMDpO-HvigKUwoDgDQ&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=Hammeren%2C%20Denmark&f=false|title= Frommer's Denmark |year=2009|accessdate=22 October 2012|publisher= Active John Wiley & Sons |isbn=9780470502907|page=258}}</ref> extending over {{Convert|182|ha}} and including a number of [[caves]]. The area, which was once covered with heather and bracken, was laid bare by heavy grazing.
Hammeren features a large lake, [[Hammersø]], the largest on the island, and a deep pond, Opalsø, surrounded by the rocky slopes of a former [[granite]] quarry. Separated by a rift valley, the area is composed of about 50% rocks, 25% forest and 25% cultivated land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.studienet.dk/Opgaver/Hammers%C3%B8en--24294.aspx|title=Rapport: Hammersøen|accessdate=20 October 2012|publisher=SStuidenet}}</ref> All of Hammeren is now a protected nature reserve. There are a number of walking trails connecting Sandvig and Hammershus Slo. The path along the northern rocky face leads to [[Hammeren Lighthouse|Hammeren Fyr]], a lighthouse located at the northern tip, before proceeding along the coastal path towards the south east to the harbour, [[Hammeren Havn]].<ref name="denstoredanske.dk"/><ref name="Stone2008"/>
[[File:Bornholm - Hammeren Fyr.jpg|thumb|left|Hammeren Fyr Lighthouse.]] ==Landmarks== The thirteenth-century castle of [[Hammershus]], [[Northern Europe]]'s largest [[Middle ages|medieval]] [[fortification]], is located just to the south. There are several quarries in the vicinity.<ref name="Stone2008"/> Trails lead from nearby Hammerhus to a nature area named [[Slotslyngen]].<ref name="Stone2008"/> In addition to [[Dueodde Lighthouse]], Denmark's tallest,<ref name="unc.edu">{{cite web|url=http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/lighthouse/dnkb.htm|title=Lighthouses of Denmark: Bornholm|publisher=University of North Carolina|accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref> there are several others on the island, such as Hammeren Lighthouse, inactive since 1990.<ref name="unc.edu">{{cite web|url=http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/lighthouse/dnkb.htm|title=Lighthouses of Denmark: Bornholm|publisher=University of North Carolina|accessdate=23 October 2012}}</ref> On a clear day, views extend to the [[Sweden|Swedish]] coast.<ref name="Norie1846" /><ref name=Backpacker1978>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7t8DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA36&lpg=PA36&dq=Trails+in+Hammeren,+Denmark&source=bl&ots=bZbXcJODZn&sig=HWw_ZaWY4iMW3WX2JxsO63zWu6k&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WRCGULmbL6KDiwKgq4HQDg&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Trails%20in%20Hammeren%2C%20Denmark&f=false|title= Backpacker|year=1978|accessdate=22 October 2012|publisher= Active Interest Media, Inc.|page=36}}</ref> [[File:Salomons Kapel.jpg|thumb|right|Salomons Kapel]] Close to the coast, to the south of the Hammeren Lighthouse, the ruins of [[Salomons Kapel]] (Solomon's Chapel) can be seen. Thought to have been built by the [[Archbishop of Lund]] in the beginning of the fourteenth century, it was named after St Solomon, a [[Dominican monk]]. It was built of brick and hewn boulders in two stages: first the small rectangular church and later the porch area to the south. Remains of the altar and of brick benches along the walls can be seen. The chapel was constructed in connection with Bornholm's herring trade with the [[Hanseatic League|Hanseatic cities]] of Hamburg and Lübeck from the thirteenth to fifteenth centuries.<ref>[http://www.bornholmerguiden.dk/kirchen/salomons_kapel_bornholm/index.htm "Salomons kapel på Bornholm"], ''Bornholmer Guiden''. {{da icon}}. Retrieved 24 October 2012.</ref>
